Chartergus Lepeletier, 1836
is a neotropical genus of swarm-founding social wasps that comprises only three species:
Chartergus artifex (Christ, 1791)
( type species),
Chartergus globiventris de Saussure, 1854
, and
Chartergus metanotalis Richards, 1978
. The genus is primarily distinguished by the head with occipital carina present dorsolaterally, absence of anteromedial fovea on the pronotum, metanotum with medial tubercle, propodeum with dorsolateral carinae, and metasomal segment I compressed (
). This genus is widely distributed in South America, from Colombia to South of Mid-West Brazil (
;
). Their nests are arboreal, frequently attached to a tree branch high above the ground, and exhibit typical phragmocyttarous structure, consisting of multiple combs sessile on its own envelope, which are usually rigid and composed of long white fibers. Moreover, the nests are cylindrical or broadening downwards with a flattened-conical bottom, and grow rapidly through the construction of several layers. The entrance hole is simple and located in the ventral center of the nest, which may become funnel shaped. It is little more than one wasp’s headwidth in diameter and aligns to form an internal passage between combs (
;
).

The complete list of specimens used in our phylogenetic analyses is presented in Supplementary Material (Table S1). We used Cytochrome c oxidase I (COI) sequences extracted from off-target sequences of ultraconserved elements raw sequencing data (for details see 

). The COI is a good mitochondrial marker for systematic investigations in social wasps (

). We performed the alignment using the MAFFT v7.0 algorithm (

), available on the MAFFT webserver (https://mafft.cbrc.jp/alignment/server/), employing the GINS-i strategy and default settings. We visually inspected and corrected all alignments. The most suitable model of nucleotide evolution by codon position for COI was determined using PARTITIONFINDER2 (

) under the Bayesian information criterion. Subsequently, we concatenated the COI and morphological characters using the software MESQUITE v.3.61 (

).

In our phylogenetic analyses, we included 

Protonectarina sylveirae
(de Saussure, 1854)

, 

Brachygastra lecheguana
(Latreille, 1804)

, and 

Protopolybia bituberculata
Silveira & Carpenter, 1996

, as outgroup taxa based on previous phylogenetic studies (

, 

; 

). We performed phylogenetic analyses using a combined dataset of morphological and molecular data, employing Maximum Parsimony (MP) and Maximum Likelihood (ML) methods. For MP analysis, we used TNT version 1.5 (

) and conducted tree search with Implicit Enumeration. Clade support was assessed using Symmetric Resampling for MP (

). For ML analysis, we used IQ-TREE v.2.2.2.6 (

) and calculated branch supports with 1000 replicates of the Shimodaira-Hasegawa approximate likelihood ratio test (SH-aLRT) (

) and parametric ultrafast bootstrap (UFBoot2) (

).

